</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">It works out that the graph of <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> stays above the <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display="LUklbXJvd0c2Iy9JK21vZHVsZW5hbWVHNiJJLFR5cGVzZXR0aW5nR0koX3N5c2xpYkdGJzYkLUkjbWlHRiQ2JVEieEYnLyUnaXRhbGljR1EldHJ1ZUYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdpdGFsaWNGJy9GM1Enbm9ybWFsRic=">LUklbXJvd0c2Iy9JK21vZHVsZW5hbWVHNiJJLFR5cGVzZXR0aW5nR0koX3N5c2xpYkdGJzYkLUkjbWlHRiQ2JVEieEYnLyUnaXRhbGljR1EldHJ1ZUYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdpdGFsaWNGJy9GM1Enbm9ybWFsRic=</Equation>-axis, just touching it in two places.  We first show this graphically:</Text-field>
<Group labelreference="L227" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plot(g(Pi,x),x=-1..3);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="Maple Plot" layout="Maple Plot"><Plot height="500.0" originalheight="500.0" type="two-dimensional" width="500.0" originalwidth="500.0" plot-scale="1.0" plot-xtrans="0.0" plot-ytrans="0.0" gridlinevisibility="1" legendvisibility="false" input="_ATTRIBUTE(&quot;input&quot; = [TABLE([1 = plot, 2 = [(x-1-(1/2)*2^(1/2))^2*(x+1-(1/2)*2^(1/2))^2/(x^4+1)], 3 = (x = -1 .. 3)]), &quot;originalview&quot; = [-1. .. 3., 0.157560894574454690e-4 .. 1.83210678118654791]])"></Plot></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">We now zoom in to the first point where the curve touches the axis:</Text-field>
<Group labelreference="L233" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plot(g(Pi,x),x=-.292899..-.292885,-1e-10..1e-10,numpoints=1000);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="Maple Plot" layout="Maple Plot"><Plot height="500.0" originalheight="500.0" type="two-dimensional" width="500.0" originalwidth="500.0" plot-scale="1.0" plot-xtrans="0.0" plot-ytrans="0.0" gridlinevisibility="1" legendvisibility="false" input="_ATTRIBUTE(&quot;input&quot; = [TABLE([1 = plot, 2 = [(x-1-(1/2)*2^(1/2))^2*(x+1-(1/2)*2^(1/2))^2/(x^4+1)], 3 = (x = -.292899 .. -.292885), 4 = -0.1e-9 .. 0.1e-9, 5 = (numpoints = 1000)]), &quot;originalview&quot; = [-.292899000000000020 .. -.292885000000000006, 0.177122325790378853e-15 .. 0.268219666677592269e-9]])"></Plot></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">To see why this works algebraically, note that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> and <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  Putting this in the definition of <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> gives the following:</Text-field>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L239" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">g(Pi,x);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="">KigsKEkieEc2IiIiIiEiIkYmKiQiIiMjRiZGKSNGJ0YpRiksKEYkRiZGJkYmRihGK0YpLCYqJEYkIiIlRiZGJkYmRic=</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">As the square or fourth power of any real number is nonnegative, this formula shows that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> for all <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display="LUklbXJvd0c2Iy9JK21vZHVsZW5hbWVHNiJJLFR5cGVzZXR0aW5nR0koX3N5c2xpYkdGJzYkLUkjbWlHRiQ2JVEieEYnLyUnaXRhbGljR1EldHJ1ZUYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdpdGFsaWNGJy9GM1Enbm9ybWFsRic=">LUklbXJvd0c2Iy9JK21vZHVsZW5hbWVHNiJJLFR5cGVzZXR0aW5nR0koX3N5c2xpYkdGJzYkLUkjbWlHRiQ2JVEieEYnLyUnaXRhbGljR1EldHJ1ZUYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdpdGFsaWNGJy9GM1Enbm9ybWFsRic=</Equation>.</Text-field><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal"><Font size="14" style="Text" bold="true">(c) </Font>It turns out that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  To see this graphically, compare the two plots below.</Text-field>
<Group labelreference="L240" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plot(1-8*g(a,0),a=-10..10);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="Maple Plot" layout="Maple Plot"><Plot height="500.0" originalheight="500.0" type="two-dimensional" width="500.0" originalwidth="500.0" plot-scale="1.0" plot-xtrans="0.0" plot-ytrans="0.0" gridlinevisibility="1" legendvisibility="false" input="_ATTRIBUTE(&quot;input&quot; = [TABLE([1 = plot, 2 = [1-8*(-1-sin((1/4)*a))*(-1-cos((1/4)*a))*(1-sin((1/4)*a))*(1-cos((1/4)*a))], 3 = (a = -10 .. 10)]), &quot;originalview&quot; = [-10. .. 10., -.99999977919638883 .. .99999998453958128]])"></Plot></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L246" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plot(cos(a),a=-10..10);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="Maple Plot" layout="Maple Plot"><Plot height="500.0" originalheight="500.0" type="two-dimensional" width="500.0" originalwidth="500.0" plot-scale="1.0" plot-xtrans="0.0" plot-ytrans="0.0" gridlinevisibility="1" legendvisibility="false" input="_ATTRIBUTE(&quot;input&quot; = [TABLE([1 = plot, 2 = [cos(a)], 3 = (a = -10 .. 10)]), &quot;originalview&quot; = [-9.97499999999999964 .. 9.97499999999999964, -1. .. 1.]])"></Plot></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">However, Maple's simplification commands are not clever enough to work this out:</Text-field>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L252" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">1-8*g(a,0);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="">LCYiIiJGIyoqLCYhIiJGIy1JJHNpbkc2JCUqcHJvdGVjdGVkR0koX3N5c2xpYkc2IjYjLCRJImFHRiwjRiMiIiVGJkYjLCZGJkYjLUkkY29zR0YpRi1GJkYjLCZGI0YjRidGJkYjLCZGI0YjRjNGJkYjISIp</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L253" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">simplify(1-8*g(a,0));</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="">LCgqJC1JJGNvc0c2JCUqcHJvdGVjdGVkR0koX3N5c2xpYkc2IjYjLCRJImFHRikjIiIiIiIlRi8iIikqJEYkIiIjISIpRi5GLg==</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">If we give Maple a hint by asking it to simplify <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> instead, it does succeed in working out that this is zero:</Text-field>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L254" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">simplify(1-8*g(a,0)-cos(a));</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="LUkjbW5HNiMvSSttb2R1bGVuYW1lRzYiSSxUeXBlc2V0dGluZ0dJKF9zeXNsaWJHRic2JFEiMEYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdub3JtYWxGJw==">IiIh</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">Here is a trick that persuades Maple to convert <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> to <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  It is based on De Moivre's Theorem, which will be covered in the course on complex numbers.</Text-field>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L255" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">simplify(convert(1-8*g(a,0),exp));</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="">LUkkY29zRzYkJSpwcm90ZWN0ZWRHSShfc3lzbGliRzYiNiNJImFHRic=</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group><Text-field style="Normal" layout="Normal">To do this simplification by hand, note that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>, which is the same as <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  Similarly, we have <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  Putting these together, we see that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>, which is the same as <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  Using the standard formula <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>, this simplifies to <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>.  We can then use the standard formula <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> to deduce that <Equation executable="false" style="2D Comment" input-equation="" display=""></Equation>. </Text-field><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">(d)</Text-field>
